## THE TEN COMMANDMENTS OF RIGHTEOUS CODE

### 1. THOU SHALT HAVE ZERO TYPESCRIPT ERRORS
- NO TS ERRORS SHALL EXIST IN THE CODEBASE
- ALL TYPE SAFETY SHALL BE MAINTAINED
- NO IMPLICIT ANY TYPES SHALL BE TOLERATED

### 2. THOU SHALT HAVE ZERO ESLINT ERRORS
- NO LINTING VIOLATIONS SHALL BE PERMITTED
- ALL CODE SHALL FOLLOW THE SACRED STYLE GUIDE
- NO UNUSED VARIABLES SHALL REMAIN

### 3. THOU SHALT USE PROPER TYPE SAFETY
- NO TYPE ASSERTIONS SHALL BE USED UNLESS ABSOLUTELY NECESSARY
- ALL PROPERTY ACCESS SHALL USE PROPER TYPE GUARDS
- NO UNSAFE MEMBER ACCESS SHALL BE TOLERATED

### 4. THOU SHALT HANDLE NULL AND UNDEFINED PROPERLY
- ALL NULL CHECKS SHALL BE EXPLICIT
- NO OPTIONAL CHAINING SHALL BE USED WITHOUT PROPER NULL CHECKS
- ALL UNDEFINED VALUES SHALL BE HANDLED GRACEFULLY

### 5. THOU SHALT USE PROPER ERROR HANDLING
- ALL ERRORS SHALL BE CAUGHT AND HANDLED
- NO CONSOLE.ERROR SHALL BE USED IN PRODUCTION CODE
- ALL EXCEPTIONS SHALL BE HANDLED SILENTLY OR LOGGED PROPERLY

### 6. THOU SHALT ELIMINATE ALL UNUSED CODE
- NO UNUSED IMPORTS SHALL REMAIN
- NO UNUSED VARIABLES SHALL EXIST
- NO UNUSED FUNCTIONS SHALL BE PRESERVED

### 7. THOU SHALT USE PROPER FUNCTION SIGNATURES
- ALL FUNCTION PARAMETERS SHALL BE TYPED
- NO ANY TYPES SHALL BE USED IN FUNCTION SIGNATURES
- ALL RETURN TYPES SHALL BE EXPLICIT

### 8. THOU SHALT MAINTAIN CONSISTENT CODING STYLE
- ALL CODE SHALL FOLLOW THE ESTABLISHED PATTERNS
- NO INCONSISTENT FORMATTING SHALL BE TOLERATED
- ALL NAMING CONVENTIONS SHALL BE FOLLOWED

### 9. THOU SHALT USE PROPER INTERFACE DEFINITIONS
- ALL INTERFACES SHALL BE PROPERLY DEFINED
- NO DUPLICATE INTERFACES SHALL EXIST
- ALL PROPERTIES SHALL BE TYPED CORRECTLY

### 10. THOU SHALT COMMIT ONLY RIGHTEOUS CODE
- NO CODE SHALL BE COMMITTED WITH ERRORS
- ALL CHANGES SHALL BE TESTED AND VERIFIED
- THE CODEBASE SHALL REMAIN PURE AND RIGHTEOUS

## SACRED ENFORCEMENT RULES

### BEFORE EVERY COMMIT:
1. Run `npm run type-check` - MUST RETURN 0 ERRORS
2. Run `npm run lint` - MUST RETURN 0 ERRORS
3. Verify all tests pass
4. Ensure no console statements remain in production code

### FORBIDDEN PRACTICES:
- Using `any` type without explicit justification
- Using type assertions (`as Type`) without proper type guards
- Leaving unused variables or imports
- Using console.log/console.error in production code
- Ignoring TypeScript or ESLint errors
- Committing code with errors

### REQUIRED PRACTICES:
- Explicit null/undefined checks
- Proper error handling with try-catch
- Type-safe property access
- Consistent naming conventions
- Proper interface definitions
- Clean, readable code structure

